\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
A SIMPLE PRIOR FREE METHOD FOR NON-RIGID STRUCTURE FROM MOTION FACTORIZATION
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Yuchao Dai , Hongdong Li , Mingyi He
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
About : 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This paper proposes a simple prior free method for solving non rigid structure
 from motion factorization problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The success of the paper lies in the fact that it doesnot assume constraints
 on non rigidity o camera motions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The paper discusses about the factorisation problem of measurement matrix
 and techniques employed to accurately extract non-rigid shape and camera
 motion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Introduction :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tomasi - kanade Factorization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we track P feature points over F frames in an image stream.
 Let the trajectories of image coordinates be 
\begin_inset Formula ${(u_{fp},v_{fp})}$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula $f=1,2,...F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1,2,......P$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The measurement matrix is formed as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $W=\left[\begin{array}{ccccc}
u_{11} & u_{12} & . & . & u_{1p}\\
u_{21} & . & . & . & u_{2p}\\
. & . & . & . & .\\
. & . & . & . & .\\
. & . & . & . & .\\
v_{11} & v_{12} & . & . & v_{1p}\\
. & . & . & . & .\\
. & . & . & . & .\\
v_{f1} & v_{f2} & v_{f3} & . & v_{fp}
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The individual elements are substracted from mean of each frame.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $u_{ij}=u_{ij}-meanx_{i}$
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $meanx_{i}=1/P\sum u_{ij}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $v_{ij}=v_{ij}-meany_{i}$
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $meany_{i}=1/P\sum v_{ij}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The new matrix is called registered rank matrix.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Coordinate frame orientation is adjusted that world origin is at centroid
 of P world points whose P feature points are tracked in image stream.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With such a arrangement W can decomposed into RS where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R=\left[\begin{array}{c}
i_{1}^{'}\\
i_{2}^{'}\\
.\\
.\\
.\\
j_{1}^{'}\\
j_{2}^{'}\\
.\\
.\\
j_{f}^{'}
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{1}$
\end_inset

 are along scan lines and columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{st}$
\end_inset

 image in the stream.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(dimension=2F\times3)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
s_{1} & . & . & s_{p}\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is the shape matrix .
\begin_inset Formula $(dimension=3\times P)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we come most important and powerful theorem of factorization which is
 rank theorem .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
RANK THEOREM:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Without noise the registered measrement matrix is atmost rank 3.Even if the
 matrix is noisy the best possible shape and rotation estimate is obtained
 by considering only the three greatest singular values of W.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
By using SVD decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{'}=U^{'}D^{'}V^{'}$
\end_inset

 .Then we can assign 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{'}=U^{'}D^{'}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{'}=V^{'}$
\end_inset

.
 This solution is true only up to 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $R=R^{'}Q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S=Q^{-1}S^{'}$
\end_inset

 are also possible solutions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To find 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 we introduce metric constraints for ex : 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}\times i{}_{1}^{'}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}\times i{}_{2}^{'}=0$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Even now the solution is determined to a 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 rotation matrix hence another constraint that world frame is initially
 parallel to first frame.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Finally rotation matrix and shape matrix can be found for each frame and
 the results were as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename 26-04-2013 16-45-01.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bregler's work:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Abstract :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This paper addresses the problem of recovering 3D non-rigid shape models
 from image sequences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Here 3D shapes in each frame is a linear combination of a set of basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This paper demonstrates a new technique for recovering 3D non-rigid shape
 models from 2D image sequences recorded with a single camera.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
All existing methods for nonrigid 3D shapes either require an a-priori model
 or require multiple views.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This is the first algorithm that can tackle this problem without the use
 of a prior model and without multiple view or other 3D input.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Explanation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The shape of the non-rigid object is described as a keyframe basis set
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1},S_{2},S_{3}........$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The shape of a specific configuration is a linear combination of basis set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S=\sum_{i=1}^{k}L_{i}S_{i}(dimension=3\times P)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{ccccc}
u1 & u2 & . & . & up\\
v1 & v2 & . & . & vp
\end{array}\right]=R\times S+T(u_{i},v_{i})$
\end_inset

are 2-D image points in a frame.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\begin_inset Formula $R=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
r1 & r2 & r3\\
r4 & r5 & r6
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

contains first two rows of rotation matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We eliminate T by subtracting the mean of all 2D points, and henceforth
 can assume that S is centered at the origin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
After adding temporal index to each frame we form measurement matrix W.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $W=\left[\begin{array}{cccccc}
l_{1}^{1}R^{1} & . & . & . & . & l_{k}^{1}R^{1}\\
. & . & . & . & . & .\\
. & . & . & . & . & .\\
l_{1}^{N}R^{N} & . & . & . & . & l_{k}^{N}R^{N}
\end{array}\right]\times\left[\begin{array}{c}
S_{1}\\
S_{2}\\
.\\
.\\
S_{K}
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

for N frames 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=QB(dimensionofQ=2N\times3KandB=3K\times P)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Q can be factorised into configuration weights and pose matrix in each frame
 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transformation matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 maps all 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{t}$
\end_inset

 into an orthonormal
\begin_inset Formula $R_{t}=R_{t}^{'}\times G$
\end_inset

.
 which is found using least square methods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename 26-04-2013 21-51-02.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Track the eye brows, upper and lower eye lids, 5 nose points, outer and
 inner boundary of the lips, and the chin contour using 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
apperance based 2D tracking technique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Paper work:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In a 2004 paper, Xiao et al.
 proved that the problem itself is indeed ill-posed or under-constrained,
 in the sense that, based on the orthonormality constraint alone, one cannot
 recover the non-rigid shape bases and the corresponding shape coefficients
 uniquely.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To resolve this ambiguity, Xiao et al.
 suggested to add extraneous “basis constraints” so as to make the system
 well-constrained.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Akhter et al.
 made an important theoretical progress in [2] which reveals that: although
 the ambiguity in shape basis is inherent, the 3D shape itself can be recovered
 uniquely without ambiguity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Based on the linear combination model , the non-rigid shape Si belongs to
  
\begin_inset Formula $R(3\times P)$
\end_inset

 can be represented as a linear combination of K shape bases Bk belong to
 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $R(3\times P)$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 with shape coefficients cik as
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}=\sum cikBk$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Under orthographic camera model, the coordinates of the 2D image points
 observed at frame i are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{i}=R_{i}S_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $R{}_{i}$
\end_inset

 contains first two rows of ith camera rotation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $W=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
C_{11}R_{1} & \ldots & C_{1k}R_{1}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
C_{f1}R_{1} & \cdots & C_{fk}R_{f}
\end{array}\right]\times\left[\begin{array}{c}
B_{1}\\
\vdots\\
\vdots\\
B_{k}
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
= 
\begin_inset Formula $R(C\times I{}_{3})B$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $R=blkdiag(R_{1},R_{2},R_{3}............)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=\Pi\times B$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi=3\times k$
\end_inset

 and dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $B=3\times k$
\end_inset

 )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However this decomposition is not unique as any non singular matrix G can
 be inserted between as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi GG^{-1}B$
\end_inset

 .
 This G which rectifies 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

 is called Euclidean corrective matrix .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Orthonormality constraints in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

 matrix can be imposed to recover a Gram Matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $Q{}_{k}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}=G_{k}G{}^{T}{}_{k}$
\end_inset

.(dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}=3k\times3k$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Akhter et al showed that the fundamental ambiguity does not necessarily
 lead to an ambiguous shape .
 Orthonormality constraints alone is in fact sufficient to recover a unique
 (unambiguous) non-rigid shape (provided that a previously-overlooked rank-3
 constraint on 
\begin_inset Formula $Q{}_{k}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Denote ith double rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\Pi}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\Pi}{}_{2i-1:2i}$
\end_inset

and kth triplet og 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $G{}_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2i-1}*Q_{k}*\Pi_{2i-1}^{'}={}_{2i}*Q_{k}*\Pi^{'}{}_{2i},\Pi_{2i-1}*Q_{k}*\Pi^{'}{}_{2i}=0$
\end_inset

------- (Eq)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Part*
Theorem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the solutions of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}$
\end_inset

to linear system of (Eq) form a linear subspace of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $2K^{2}-K.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above equation is converted into the form 
\begin_inset Formula $Aq_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{k}=vec(Q_{k})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $9k^{2}$
\end_inset

column vector .
 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the nullspace of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Part*
Intersection theorem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under nondegenerate and noise-free conditions, any correct solution of Qk
 (i.e.
 the Gram matrix of a column-triplet of the true Euclidean corrective matrix
 Gk) must lie in the intersection of the (2K2−K) dimensional null-space
 of A and a rank-3 positive semi-definite matrix cone, i.e., Qk belongs to
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula ${Avec(Q_{k})=0}∩{Qk\succ0}∩{rank(Q_{k})=3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The three steps to solve the above algorithm are 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

easurement noise may increase rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}$
\end_inset

 and the problem is to minimise 
\begin_inset Formula $rank(Q_{k})$
\end_inset

.
 Nuclear norm minimization is the tightest convex relaxation for the rank
 minimization problem (above) which is NP-hard.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $trace(Q_{k}^{*})=rank(Q_{k}^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 So the problem reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula $min(trace(Q_{k})$
\end_inset

) such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Avec(Q_{k})=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}$
\end_inset

 is semi-definite matrix.This is a standard semi definite programming problem
 (SDP) of fixed size 
\begin_inset Formula $(2k^{2}-k)$
\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once Gk find similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{1},G_{2},.....$
\end_inset

 and form G matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Once 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{k}$
\end_inset

 is solved, the rotation at every frame 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,···,F$
\end_inset

 can be solved by using
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Pi}_{2i-1:2i}G_{k}$
\end_inset

 = 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{ik}R_{i}$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,...F$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Estimate S by Rank Minimisation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
valid solution to shape matrix is formulated as following rank minisization
 problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $rank(s)\leq3\times k$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $W=RS$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution to the above problem is unique and is given as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S=R^{\dagger}W=(R^{T}(RR^{T})^{-1})W$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

